Habitat: 'casually-maintained', wet meadow (i.e., in 2015 it was mowed, planted with trees, portions of it were brush-hogged a couple of times, and then the area was pretty much left alone). Area dominated by various species of Goldenrod (Solidago spp.), Arrowleaf Tearthumb (Polygonum sagittatum), New York Ironweed (Vernonia novaeboracensis), and Calico Aster (Symphyotrichum lateriflorum), with an 'understory' of Poison Ivy (Toxicodendron radicans). The brush-hogged areas are dominated by Multiflora Rose (Rosa multiflora), with abundant Allegheny Blackberry (Rubus allegheniensis).

Visual Description: This organism is a grey color, with spots on its wings. It has 6 legs. When it expands its wings, there is a red color on the backside of the wings. It is approximately 2 inches long. Habitat: This organism was found on the sidewalk. It was originally sitting on top of a tree, until it flew onto the sidewalk. Geographic Distribution: This organism can be found in China. It is an invasive species that has started appearing in North America, especially in colder regions, such as the State, Pennsylvania. Reference: https://www.invasivespeciesinfo.gov/terrestrial/invertebrates/spotted-lanternfly#:~:text=USDA%20.,Berks%20County%2C%20Pennsylvania%20in%202014.

The spotted lanternfly is an invasive species that originated in Asia and has spread to the United States, specifically here in Pennsylvania. Full-grown adults are a few centimeters long, with black heads and gray-ish colored wings with black spots. Underneath the wings is a bright red color, which can be seen when they fly or spread their wings.
